    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2835587976" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2835587976" />
    <a title="Tanya" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/15698555-tanya"><img alt="Tanya" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1602837639p2/15698555.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2835587976?book_show_action=true">Feb 13, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanya" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanya" href="/user/show/15698555-tanya">Tanya</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13172241-possessing-the-secret-of-joy">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2835587976" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18428326231528716424">I read Walker’s <i>The Color Purple</i> some years ago and loved it, but I picked up <i>Possessing the Secret of Joy</i> not because of its loose connection to it, but rather because it’s the novel that inspired Tori Amos’ 1994 song <i>Cornflake Girl</i>, one of her best known and commercially successful hits. I went into this novel with that particular read—women betraying women—in mind, and that’s what struck and horrified me most, other than the pretty graphic scenes of female genital mutilation and its aftermath</span>
  <span id="freeText18428326231528716424" style="display:none">I read Walker’s <i>The Color Purple</i> some years ago and loved it, but I picked up <i>Possessing the Secret of Joy</i> not because of its loose connection to it, but rather because it’s the novel that inspired Tori Amos’ 1994 song <i>Cornflake Girl</i>, one of her best known and commercially successful hits. I went into this novel with that particular read—women betraying women—in mind, and that’s what struck and horrified me most, other than the pretty graphic scenes of female genital mutilation and its aftermath. The practice may have been instituted by the patriarchy, but it’s the women that uphold it, and this novel makes you reckon with the illusion of sisterhood. It’s the mother, the one person supposed to take care of you, that takes her daughter to be mutilated, just as she has been, and her mother before her—all in the name of a sick misogynist ritual.<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>“If you lie to yourself about your own pain, you will be killed by those who will claim you enjoyed it.”</i>
</blockquote><br /><br />The story follows Tashi, a minor character from <i>The Color Purple</i>, who has left Olinka, a fictional African nation, and now lives in the US with her American husband… but she feels deeply torn between the two cultures, and chooses to undergo female circumcision. The procedure killed her older sister, who bled to death, but instead of counting her lucky stars that she made it out intact, Tashi feels as if she is betraying her roots, and goes back to Olinka to have it performed as a young adult, after already having experienced the joys of female pleasure. As a result of the cultural, emotional, and physical trauma, she goes mad.<br /><br /><i>Possessing the Secret of Joy</i> is unflinching and visceral (how could it not be?), and had a wide-reaching societal impact as far as education about, and activism against, genital mutilation goes, with a portion of the royalties going towards those causes. With that said, it made for a very fragmented, somewhat sloppy reading experience—it’s a short read, and yet it is divided into twenty parts and even more chapters, with multiple POVs, time-jumps, and a very ambitious scope as far as anthropology and etymology goes… but it turns out that that’s all fictional, and I’m just not sure if a story advocating against a very real practice is best served by such a narrative approach. Ultimately, in my case, this choice definitely lessened the emotional impact of the novel.<br /><br />I also read this during the COVID-pandemic, as vaccines are beginning to roll out amid a staggering number of people still calling it a hoax or refusing vaccination for dubious, crazy reasons (and I’m including my own parents in this group), so I couldn’t help but resent Walker’s almost throw-away implication that the oral polio vaccine caused the AIDS epidemic in Africa, which has since been debunked as nothing but a conspiracy theory. Too bad, the damage is done—those rumors are one of the leading reasons why polio has not yet been eradicated. There were also valid points about African colonization thrown in there, but it’s all a bit too unstructured, and important messages are lost in a short novel that tries to address too many things at once.<br /><br />I don’t doubt that Walker’s intentions were honorable and her motives genuine, but the way she went about it all was less than ideal, in my eyes. Despite all the listed detractors, and the messy narrative style which still has me a little confused about the timeline of events, I was affected by <i>Possessing the Secret of Joy</i>… and educated, as well. I thought excision was as far as FGM went, but I learned about the horrors of infibulation, the worst type of female circumcision, through this book. Clearly, if a thirty-year-old novel is the first time I, a relatively well-read feminist, heard of such a vile practice, we as a society don’t speak of it enough. It must stop.<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i>“These settler cannibals. Why don’t they just steal our land, mine our gold, chop down our forests, pollute our rivers, enslave us to work on their farms, fuck us, devour our flesh and leave us alone? Why must they also write about how much joy we possess?”</i>
</blockquote></span>
  <a data-text-id="18428326231528716424" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


