    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1219557149" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1219557149" />
    <a title="P. Kirby" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5112326-p-kirby"><img alt="P. Kirby" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442534274p2/5112326.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1219557149?book_show_action=true">Oct 22, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="P. Kirby" class="user" itemprop="url" name="P. Kirby" href="/user/show/5112326-p-kirby">P. Kirby</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/13172241-possessing-the-secret-of-joy">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5112326-p-kirby?shelf=general-fiction">general-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1219557149" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16788352594391735737">There&apos;s no question that a practice that mutilates women with the goal of making them look like Barbie dolls--i.e., with a flat, featureless landscape instead of actual genitalia--is inhumane and nothing that should be condoned as &quot;tradition.&quot; The problem, however, with <i>Possessing the Secret Joy</i>, a novel about Tashi, a woman who has suffered this brutal practice and continues to struggle with the physical and emotional scars for many decades after, is that the narrative structure is messy and la</span>
  <span id="freeText16788352594391735737" style="display:none">There's no question that a practice that mutilates women with the goal of making them look like Barbie dolls--i.e., with a flat, featureless landscape instead of actual genitalia--is inhumane and nothing that should be condoned as "tradition." The problem, however, with <i>Possessing the Secret Joy</i>, a novel about Tashi, a woman who has suffered this brutal practice and continues to struggle with the physical and emotional scars for many decades after, is that the narrative structure is messy and lacks the emotional power I expected.<br /><br />The story is told in alternating POVs (one per chapter): Tashi, her husband Adam, their son Benny, Tashi's friend, Tashi's shrink, Adam's mistress (yes, his mistress), and Adam's son with the mistress. There may be another POV in there, as well. After a while, the various voices in the novel started to blur--none are particularly well-defined or possess unique character. The story also tries to address other issues beyond female genital mutilation--AIDs, the colonization of Africa by Western powers, etc. All issues worth exploring, but again, the narrative structure is so unstructured, that the message gets lost in the method.<br /><br />The basic plot follows the "mystery" of Tashi's crime, the why and how she came to be imprisoned in an African jail, despite her obvious American citizenship. The slow unfolding of this mystery is the only thing that kept me reading. Tashi, herself, is too much the unreliable narrator. I get what Walker was trying to do; demonstrate the extent to which Tashi struggles with a sense of self, but...I never connected with her. <br /><br />I confess, Tashi's "circumcision," performed with her consent, as an adult, didn't move me as much as it should have. Tashi's motivation, to appease a messiah-like political figure, to prove her African-ness, seemed inadequate. And yes, I know that's the mindset of a privileged Western woman talking, but still...Tashi's plight didn't move me as much as that of the very young girls who are forced to undergo the mutilation.<br /><br />Nevertheless, <i>Possessing the Secret of Joy</i> is worth reading, if only for its value in shedding light on an absolutely abominable practice that quite literally cripples thousands of women in Africa and the Middle East. <br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="16788352594391735737" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


